{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}
[[File:Federer Cincinnati (2007).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Roger Federer]] has received the award four times, more than any other athlete in history.]]
The '''BBC Overseas Sports Personality of the Year'''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4514838.stm|title=Warne lands BBC Overseas accolade|date=11 December 2005|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 January 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061224012759/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4514838.stm| archivedate=24 December 2006<!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> is an award presented at the annual [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year]] award ceremony. The award is presented to a non-British sportsperson considered to have made the most substantial contribution to a sport in that year. The award was decided by a panel of over 30 sporting journalists. Each panellist voted for their top two choices; their first preference was awarded two points, and their second preference was awarded one point. The winning sportsperson had the most total points. In the case of a points tie, the sportsperson chosen as first preference by the most panellists is the winner. If this is also a tie the award is shared.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/sports_personality_of_the_year/7735134.stm|title=Sports Personality voting & judging: Terms & conditions|date=18 November 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 January 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090118025110/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/sports_personality_of_the_year/7735134.stm| archivedate= 18 January 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In 2015 the public voted for this award.

The Overseas Personality award was first presented in 1960, six years after the BBC Sports Personality of the Year award was introduced. The first recipient of the award was Australian [[Middle distance track event|middle distance]] runner [[Herb Elliott]].<ref name="stats">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tv_and_radio/sports_personality_of_the_year/7659905.stm|title=Sports Personality facts and figures|publisher=BBC|date=9 October 2008|accessdate=3 January 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081217122029/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tv_and_radio/sports_personality_of_the_year/7659905.stm| archivedate= 17 December 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Since then, the award has been presented to 49 sportspersons. Swiss tennis player [[Roger Federer]] has won the award four times. American boxer [[Muhammad Ali]] and Jamaican [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]] [[Usain Bolt]] have both won the award three times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport-news/other-sport/2007/12/10/joe-calzaghe-named-sports-personality-of-the-year-55578-20228911/ |title=Joe Calzaghe named Sports Personality of the Year |date=10 December 2007 |work=[[Daily Post (Wales)|Daily Post]] |accessdate=10 January 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513051548/http://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport-news/other-sport/2007/12/10/joe-calzaghe-named-sports-personality-of-the-year-55578-20228911/ |archivedate=13 May 2008 |df= }}</ref> The award has been shared on three occasions—by [[Ron Clarke]] and [[Gary Player]] in 1965, [[Eusébio]] and [[Garfield Sobers]] in 1966, and [[Evander Holyfield]] and [[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]] in 1996.<ref name="Fifty facts">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/11_november/20/spoty_50_facts.shtml|title=50th Sports Personality of the Year: Facts and figures|date=11 November 2003|publisher=BBC|accessdate=15 February 2009}}</ref> The husband-and-wife skating duo of [[Oleg Protopopov]] and [[Ludmila Belousova]] are the only pair to have won the award, doing so in 1968.<ref name="propotov"/> Belousova was the first woman to become Overseas Personality—she was also the oldest, aged 33. [[George T. D. Moore|George Moore]] is the oldest recipient of the award, winning in 1967 aged 44. The youngest recipient of the award is [[Nadia Comăneci]], who won in 1976 at age 15. [[Boris Becker]], who was 18 when he won in 1985, is the youngest male to have won.<ref name="Fifty facts"/>

Twenty different countries have been represented by the award winners. United States sportspersons have won the award the most times, having had nineteen recipients, two of whom shared the award. Three cricketers have received the award -- [[Garfield Sobers]] of Barbados, [[Brian Lara]] of Trinidad and Tobago (both of whom played for the [[West Indies cricket team]]), and [[Shane Warne]] of Australia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2004/apr/10/featuresreviews.guardianreview4 |title=Batting on |accessdate=4 January 2009 |author=Mike Selvey|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 April 2004 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/west_indies/6574317.stm|title=Legend Lara to end Windies career|accessdate=4 January 2009|author=Martin Gough|publisher=BBC|date=19 April 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090204140647/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/west_indies/6574317.stm| archivedate=4 February 2009 | deadurl= no}}</ref> Thirteen sporting disciplines have been represented; tennis has the highest representation, with fifteen recipients. The most recent recipient in 2017 was Swiss tennis player Roger Federer.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/sports-personality/42323268 | date = 15 December 2017 | accessdate = 15 December 2017 | publisher = BBC Sport | title = BBC Sports Personality 2017: Roger Federer wins BBC overseas award for record fourth time}}</ref>

Only one winner has ever been stripped of the award – US cyclist [[Lance Armstrong]], whose 2003 award was rescinded by the BBC following the UCI's 2012 decision to strip Armstrong of his titles and ban him for life from the sport.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/other-sports/bbc-strip-lance-armstrong-of-award-8423732.html | work = [[London Evening Standard]] | accessdate = 27 March 2013 | date = 18 December 2012 | title = BBC strip Lance Armstrong of award }}</ref>

